            this.resource.close();
        } finally {
            super.finalize();
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `MyClass` constructor creates a new `SomeResource` object and assigns it to the `resource` field. When the `MyClass` object is garbage collected, the `finalize()` method is called. This method calls the `close()` method on the `resource` object to clean up any resources used by the object.

Note that `finalize()` is not guaranteed to be called immediately when an object becomes eligible for garbage collection, and it may not be called at all in some cases. Therefore, it's generally not recommended to rely on `finalize()` for critical cleanup tasks. Instead, you should explicitly release resources when they are no longer needed, using the appropriate methods for the resource type (such as `close()` for a `java.io.Closeable` resource).

